00:01:08.830 --> 00:01:13.620
And I want to just give a round of applause
to Natalie Foster, Jim Pugh, and Tyler who's

00:01:13.620 --> 00:01:15.580
taking my picture right now.

00:01:15.580 --> 00:01:21.140
[Applause]
&gt;&gt;Van Jones: So you guys just, just turn around.

00:01:21.140 --> 00:01:24.490
So, since it was such a short introduction
which I kind of appreciate.

00:01:24.490 --> 00:01:28.950
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Van Jones: I was, that was good.

00:01:28.950 --> 00:01:33.120
For people who may have missed some episodes
in the Van Jones sitcom.

00:01:33.120 --> 00:01:37.979
I used to be a grass-roots outsider.

00:01:37.979 --> 00:01:39.810
In the Bay Area.

00:01:39.810 --> 00:01:42.869
And I used to work with low income kids.

00:01:42.869 --> 00:01:44.300
Kids of color.

00:01:44.300 --> 00:01:48.080
My job was trying to get kids out of jail
and into jobs.

00:01:48.080 --> 00:01:54.409
And discovered that there was a big wave of
jobs coming in the green sector, in the clean

00:01:54.409 --> 00:01:55.670
tech sector.

00:01:55.670 --> 00:01:59.770
And so I came up with this great slogan, 'Green
Jobs Not Jails'.

00:01:59.770 --> 00:02:00.770
You see.

00:02:00.770 --> 00:02:03.430
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Van Jones: Which I thought was genius.

00:02:03.430 --> 00:02:06.870
[Laughter]
Van Jones: And it wound up turning my life

00:02:06.870 --> 00:02:14.950
completely upside down because it turns out
at that point in time if you went into Oakland

00:02:14.950 --> 00:02:20.579
and you talked about green jobs they would
say, "I'm for that you mean jobs with money?"

00:02:20.579 --> 00:02:23.889
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Van Jones: I'm like, no.

00:02:23.889 --> 00:02:26.010
And so big education on that side.

00:02:26.010 --> 00:02:28.659
And then on the clean tech side, they were
for the green.

00:02:28.659 --> 00:02:30.620
They didn't understand the connection between
the jails thing.

00:02:30.620 --> 00:02:35.730
So it wound up being a really tough thing
to sort through but we were able to achieve

00:02:35.730 --> 00:02:36.870
something in Oakland.

00:02:36.870 --> 00:02:39.519
And it was called the Green jobs Corps.

00:02:39.519 --> 00:02:48.319
When we got the Oakland city Council in 2007
to pass I guess a piece of local legislation

00:02:48.319 --> 00:02:54.169
that led a lot of young kids in the community
get trained to put up solar panels.

00:02:54.169 --> 00:02:56.250
And to weatherize homes.

00:02:56.250 --> 00:03:01.510
And so it was a huge light bulb moment for
a lot of people.

00:03:01.510 --> 00:03:06.980
And there was a woman named Nancy Pelosi who
at the time when we first started was just

00:03:06.980 --> 00:03:09.559
getting underway as Speaker of the House.

00:03:09.559 --> 00:03:14.810
And she took me and my friends to Washington
DC and we got this guy named George W. Bush,

00:03:14.810 --> 00:03:20.980
who you may have heard of, to sign into law
something called the Green Jobs Act to make

00:03:20.980 --> 00:03:23.129
that possible all across country.

00:03:23.129 --> 00:03:26.599
And I wrote a book and it came out and it
was called 'The Green Collar Economy', also

00:03:26.599 --> 00:03:28.269
on sale.

00:03:28.269 --> 00:03:32.370
[Laughter]
And a guy named Barack Obama read it.

00:03:32.370 --> 00:03:36.439
And I wound up going to the White House to
help implement some of these programs.

00:03:36.439 --> 00:03:38.709
It was the best six months of my life.

00:03:38.709 --> 00:03:41.659
Followed by the worst two weeks of my life.

00:03:41.659 --> 00:03:46.150
So, you can Google and find out about that
if you don't know about it.

00:03:46.150 --> 00:03:47.859
But I then took some time off.

00:03:47.859 --> 00:03:50.389
I taught at Princeton for a year.

00:03:50.389 --> 00:03:55.019
And I tried to kind of make sense of what
I had observed.

00:03:55.019 --> 00:04:01.999
And having been a grass-roots outsider and
then having become a White House insider and

00:04:01.999 --> 00:04:08.019
then being an outsider again I kind of had
this 360Â° view of some of the ways that people

00:04:08.019 --> 00:04:12.400
who have ideas and values like mine were just
missing each other.

00:04:12.400 --> 00:04:16.109
And missing opportunities to make a bigger
difference and a better impact.

00:04:16.109 --> 00:04:20.720
And so I wanted to write both a book to express
ideas but also to try and do something about

00:04:20.720 --> 00:04:21.720
it.

00:04:21.720 --> 00:04:23.660
For me, and I again.

00:04:23.660 --> 00:04:28.700
Before I went to work for the Administration
I could sort of kind of have a more nonpartisan

00:04:28.700 --> 00:04:29.700
pose.

00:04:29.700 --> 00:04:31.780
I kind of have to confess I'm on the left.

00:04:31.780 --> 00:04:34.350
This may shock some of you.

00:04:34.350 --> 00:04:41.280
[Laughter]
And from that perspective I remember 2008.

00:04:41.280 --> 00:04:43.820
And I remember November 2008.

00:04:43.820 --> 00:04:47.620
And I remember how that felt.

00:04:47.620 --> 00:04:51.680
My father had just passed away a few months
before.

00:04:51.680 --> 00:05:00.330
He, growing up poor in the segregated South
he had to fight just to be able to get any

00:05:00.330 --> 00:05:01.330
job.

00:05:01.330 --> 00:05:05.400
He was finally able to get a job in a school
system after lawsuits.

00:05:05.400 --> 00:05:09.740
And then he was able to become a principal
of a small junior high school.

00:05:09.740 --> 00:05:10.740
And he had grown up in poverty.

00:05:10.740 --> 00:05:11.800
He got himself out of poverty.

00:05:11.800 --> 00:05:13.800
He put himself through college.

00:05:13.800 --> 00:05:15.300
He put his little brother through college.

00:05:15.300 --> 00:05:17.330
He put his cousins through college.

00:05:17.330 --> 00:05:18.330
He put me through college.

00:05:18.330 --> 00:05:19.340
He put my sister through college.

00:05:19.340 --> 00:05:21.680
He's kind of an original bootstrapper.

00:05:21.680 --> 00:05:26.430
And then he spent the rest of his life trying
to get other kids out of poverty.

00:05:26.430 --> 00:05:35.880
And his view at the end of his life was that
kids trying to get out of poverty and into

00:05:35.880 --> 00:05:39.430
the middle class have to climb that ladder
themselves.

00:05:39.430 --> 00:05:45.330
You couldn't give them anything that would
stop a child from being poor.

00:05:45.330 --> 00:05:46.810
You can give them money.

00:05:46.810 --> 00:05:50.150
But if they're poor in their heart, or poor
in their mind, or poor in their spirit.

00:05:50.150 --> 00:05:54.000
It'll stop them from being broke but they'll
be broke again.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:57.140
To get out of poverty, you got a climb that
ladder yourself.

00:05:57.140 --> 00:05:59.530
I saw that myself in Oakland.

00:05:59.530 --> 00:06:04.940
But he also had a view, which is my view which
is that even though that child has a responsibility

00:06:04.940 --> 00:06:06.530
to climb that ladder, him or herself.

00:06:06.530 --> 00:06:09.850
Grown folks have a responsibility to.

00:06:09.850 --> 00:06:11.560
Society has a responsibility to.

00:06:11.560 --> 00:06:16.390
To make sure that each child has a ladder
to climb.

00:06:16.390 --> 00:06:18.410
And that's my basic view.

00:06:18.410 --> 00:06:21.990
And that's a view in this book that yes I'm
all for individual responsibility.

00:06:21.990 --> 00:06:23.220
I'm a dad now.

00:06:23.220 --> 00:06:26.370
I'm a lot more for it now than I was when
I was younger.

00:06:26.370 --> 00:06:29.030
Anybody here got any children?

00:06:29.030 --> 00:06:35.940
Okay so chores have a totally different meaning
when you're a parent.

00:06:35.940 --> 00:06:38.040
It's good for you.

00:06:38.040 --> 00:06:39.570
But when I was a kid I hated it.

00:06:39.570 --> 00:06:41.990
My only point is simply this.

00:06:41.990 --> 00:06:44.760
I think that the ladder's fallen over.

00:06:44.760 --> 00:06:46.680
The ladder's falling over.

00:06:46.680 --> 00:06:50.700
And if we're to be able to be a middle-class
country.

00:06:50.700 --> 00:06:54.781
If the next generation of people like my dad
are gonna be able to get out of poverty and

00:06:54.781 --> 00:06:55.781
into the middle class.

00:06:55.781 --> 00:06:59.380
And frankly if people who are in the middle
class right now are going to be saved from

00:06:59.380 --> 00:07:03.250
falling over into poverty we're gonna have
to do a lot of things differently.

00:07:03.250 --> 00:07:07.700
And one of the things that were going to have
to do is to take a real assessment of what

00:07:07.700 --> 00:07:11.370
happened to that movement for hope and change.

00:07:11.370 --> 00:07:13.370
What happened?

00:07:13.370 --> 00:07:19.570
November 2008 people were crying in the streets.

00:07:19.570 --> 00:07:21.470
Hugging.

00:07:21.470 --> 00:07:27.050
Strangers in New York, I mean that's weird.

00:07:27.050 --> 00:07:28.410
It wasn't just a partisan thing.

00:07:28.410 --> 00:07:30.260
It wasn't just Democrats and like that.

00:07:30.260 --> 00:07:34.710
There were, Republicans, people on all political,
sides of the political spectrum and divide

00:07:34.710 --> 00:07:36.200
felt moved.

00:07:36.200 --> 00:07:40.421
They thought something important had happened
or shifted in the country.

00:07:40.421 --> 00:07:43.410
And it seemed like something was possible
there.

00:07:43.410 --> 00:07:48.930
And yet within a year not only were we back
to the same kind of fighting, it felt worse.

00:07:48.930 --> 00:07:53.500
And I think that a lot of people went from
hope to heartbreak pretty fast.

00:07:53.500 --> 00:07:57.210
And I think a lot of us have been just kind
of confused since then.

00:07:57.210 --> 00:08:02.510
I think a lot of us looking at this election
coming forward have some confusion.

00:08:02.510 --> 00:08:05.980
I call it the post-hope Democrats.

00:08:05.980 --> 00:08:08.639
The post-hope Independents.

00:08:08.639 --> 00:08:15.320
Probably like this President, probably not
as in love with him as people were in 2008.

00:08:15.320 --> 00:08:19.230
Probably like a lot of what the folks in the
Occupy Movement were saying back in the fall

00:08:19.230 --> 00:08:21.100
but don't want to go get pepper sprayed.

00:08:21.100 --> 00:08:25.580
[Laughter]
So what are we supposed to do?

00:08:25.580 --> 00:08:30.169
And the book is really aimed towards the post
hope Democrats and Progressives and Independents

00:08:30.169 --> 00:08:34.169
who are trying to figure out how we make sense
of what just happened and how we go forward.

00:08:34.169 --> 00:08:40.529
My big insight that I try to share in the
book is I think the White House had the wrong

00:08:40.529 --> 00:08:42.490
view of the grassroots.

00:08:42.490 --> 00:08:45.650
I think they have the wrong theory of the
grassroots.

00:08:45.650 --> 00:08:48.939
I think the grassroots have the wrong theory
of the Presidency.

00:08:48.939 --> 00:08:55.930
And those two fundamental pieces of misunderstanding
created I think a lot of missed opportunities.

00:08:55.930 --> 00:08:59.939
So on the one hand, I think that there was
a tendency not for everybody at the national

00:08:59.939 --> 00:09:05.600
level but there certainly was a tendency for
some of the DC Democrats to think about the

00:09:05.600 --> 00:09:10.940
grassroots progressive movements almost sort
of like something that can be pulled out of

00:09:10.940 --> 00:09:15.220
the refrigerator, microwaved up and encouraged
to take action.

00:09:15.220 --> 00:09:19.980
But then put back the refrigerator without
a real sense that these are kind of living

00:09:19.980 --> 00:09:21.509
movements often.

00:09:21.509 --> 00:09:26.769
And that the movements themselves really predated
Obama's run.

00:09:26.769 --> 00:09:32.540
In fact I make the claim in the book that
the movement for hope and change did not start

00:09:32.540 --> 00:09:35.050
with Barack Obama.

00:09:35.050 --> 00:09:39.410
That Barack Obama was not the author or the
creator of the movement for hope and change.

00:09:39.410 --> 00:09:47.019
And that in fact you can see the precursors
all the way back in 2003 with the rise of

00:09:47.019 --> 00:09:50.910
the concern about the war in Iraq.

00:09:50.910 --> 00:09:58.069
And then you begin to see this sort of multiracial,
people power, technologically enabled movement

00:09:58.069 --> 00:10:01.730
starting to form that had higher hopes for
the country and wanted to change.

00:10:01.730 --> 00:10:03.170
All of that back in 2003.

00:10:03.170 --> 00:10:06.290
And you had groups like MoveOn.org that were
tapping into that.

00:10:06.290 --> 00:10:08.490
There was no one leader.

00:10:08.490 --> 00:10:13.080
There was no superstar celebrity savior that
was going to fix everything.

00:10:13.080 --> 00:10:15.220
In fact, that was the beauty of it.

00:10:15.220 --> 00:10:16.589
It was completely desegregated.

00:10:16.589 --> 00:10:22.050
And yet the New York Times called it the world's
second superpower, that movement, those millions

00:10:22.050 --> 00:10:24.009
of people that were marching against the war.

00:10:24.009 --> 00:10:27.470
We've almost forgotten that history but that
was really the start of something important.

00:10:27.470 --> 00:10:30.529
That poured right over into 2004 with Howard
Dean.

00:10:30.529 --> 00:10:34.759
2005 we had Katrina which broke people's hearts
across the country.

00:10:34.759 --> 00:10:42.350
By 2006 this movement was strong enough that
we elected Pelosi to be the Speaker of the

00:10:42.350 --> 00:10:43.350
House.

00:10:43.350 --> 00:10:49.399
Now mind you, 2004 Carl Rose said the Republicans
are gonna run the house and run the Congress

00:10:49.399 --> 00:10:51.759
for 20 or 30 years.

00:10:51.759 --> 00:10:53.649
This movement held them to 24 months.

00:10:53.649 --> 00:10:57.959
By the time you get from 2004 to 2006 there's
been a complete flip over.

00:10:57.959 --> 00:11:01.199
All of this was before Obama runs.

00:11:01.199 --> 00:11:04.279
Mainstream concern about the war, before Obama
ran.

00:11:04.279 --> 00:11:05.920
Al Gore came out.

00:11:05.920 --> 00:11:09.350
Mainstream concerns about climate and energy
before Obama ran.

00:11:09.350 --> 00:11:12.269
So there was a big movement happening in the
country.

00:11:12.269 --> 00:11:18.220
And that movement luckily met this man who
needed a movement and the movement frankly

00:11:18.220 --> 00:11:23.130
needed someone to articulate the concerns
that were beginning to rise up in the people.

00:11:23.130 --> 00:11:28.259
And luckily somebody like Obama came along
because he took this movement to a place and

00:11:28.259 --> 00:11:31.790
a level that nobody I know was even thinking
was possible.

00:11:31.790 --> 00:11:32.939
And he made history.

00:11:32.939 --> 00:11:39.499
And when the man in the movement met, he just
created this global supernova.

00:11:39.499 --> 00:11:45.769
But I think sometimes we forget as inspiring
as Obama was at that time and often is now,

00:11:45.769 --> 00:11:48.269
we the people inspired him first.

00:11:48.269 --> 00:11:50.360
That's the most important thing I can say.

00:11:50.360 --> 00:11:52.240
It was people inspired him first.

00:11:52.240 --> 00:11:56.420
He said he had no plans to run for President
in 2004, 2005.

00:11:56.420 --> 00:11:58.369
And yet something was evoked in him.

00:11:58.369 --> 00:12:00.700
He said, this is the time.

00:12:00.700 --> 00:12:04.119
Which means if there is a hope gap in America.

00:12:04.119 --> 00:12:05.850
You can't just point at Obama.

00:12:05.850 --> 00:12:07.869
You can't just blog about Obama.

00:12:07.869 --> 00:12:12.529
Yeah we have this whole phenomenon now where
people it's like, I call it, 'if only the

00:12:12.529 --> 00:12:15.750
President would read my blog'.

00:12:15.750 --> 00:12:18.819
[Laughter]
'All would be well', right?

00:12:18.819 --> 00:12:23.839
You know it's this is kind of phenomenon for
at least the past two or three years most

00:12:23.839 --> 00:12:29.930
Progressives have been in this whole kind
of the debate with Obama in their brain forgetting

00:12:29.930 --> 00:12:32.009
that we were doing stuff before Obama was
around.

00:12:32.009 --> 00:12:33.970
In fact we were doing a lot of great stuff.

00:12:33.970 --> 00:12:38.290
In fact it was because we were so active and
so passionate that we created the space for

00:12:38.290 --> 00:12:41.999
someone like him to run and to win.

00:12:41.999 --> 00:12:46.310
So on the one hand I think that there might
have been a failure to understand the grass

00:12:46.310 --> 00:12:48.730
roots by some of the folks in Washington DC.

00:12:48.730 --> 00:12:52.480
But I think also a failure for us to understand
ourselves.

00:12:52.480 --> 00:12:59.879
And that became the strange projection with
regard to Obama.

00:12:59.879 --> 00:13:05.579
We began to almost expect him to be a social
movement leader and not head of state.

00:13:05.579 --> 00:13:09.399
And I think that's a very fundamental misreading
of American history.

00:13:09.399 --> 00:13:14.040
Think about the most liberal President ever
right?

00:13:14.040 --> 00:13:15.689
Not Nixon.

00:13:15.689 --> 00:13:18.650
[Laughter]
Though he did pass a lot of cool stuff that

00:13:18.650 --> 00:13:20.329
I'm gonna talk about.

00:13:20.329 --> 00:13:21.679
But LBJ right?

00:13:21.679 --> 00:13:25.290
I think we all have to agree that LBJ is probably
the most liberal President.

00:13:25.290 --> 00:13:27.370
The war on poverty.

00:13:27.370 --> 00:13:28.389
Not on the war fine.

00:13:28.389 --> 00:13:32.600
But the war on poverty, the other war.

00:13:32.600 --> 00:13:35.459
Civil rights stuff passed, he signed like
two big civil rights bills.

00:13:35.459 --> 00:13:39.410
Probably the high point of American liberalism.

00:13:39.410 --> 00:13:44.600
Did LBJ lead the civil rights movement?

00:13:44.600 --> 00:13:46.670
You guys must've taken some history classes
at some point.

00:13:46.670 --> 00:13:50.129
I know you're at Google.

00:13:50.129 --> 00:13:51.730
[Laughter]
No, not at all.

00:13:51.730 --> 00:13:55.519
In fact there was a vigorous civil rights
movements in the streets, grassroots people.

00:13:55.519 --> 00:13:58.690
And there was a head of state, LBJ.

00:13:58.690 --> 00:14:02.790
LBJ was willing to listen to and respond favorably
to the movement.

00:14:02.790 --> 00:14:04.550
But there had to be a mover to do the moving.

00:14:04.550 --> 00:14:08.639
And I think what happened to some of us was
Obama kind of looks like a social movement

00:14:08.639 --> 00:14:09.639
leader.

00:14:09.639 --> 00:14:14.209
I mean people think he's cute.

00:14:14.209 --> 00:14:16.600
[Laughter]
Talks good.

00:14:16.600 --> 00:14:17.879
You know.

00:14:17.879 --> 00:14:20.620
And I think there was this thing well this
is MLK.

00:14:20.620 --> 00:14:23.649
And he's President, right?

00:14:23.649 --> 00:14:26.749
[Laughter]
How cool is that?

00:14:26.749 --> 00:14:30.699
And so then you kind of sit and you kinda
wait for him to do what a social movement

00:14:30.699 --> 00:14:31.699
leader would do.

00:14:31.699 --> 00:14:35.989
Which is to go and challenge the consensus
and disrupt everything and stick up for the

00:14:35.989 --> 00:14:36.989
little.

00:14:36.989 --> 00:14:40.519
But that's not what any US President has done.

00:14:40.519 --> 00:14:44.050
LBJ didn't lead the civil rights movement,
the people had to do that.

00:14:44.050 --> 00:14:50.290
FDR didn't lead the labor strikes that led
to the new deal we the people did that.

00:14:50.290 --> 00:14:57.329
Lincoln wasn't even an abolitionist that was
Frederick Douglass and John Brown and a bunch

00:14:57.329 --> 00:14:58.350
of other people.

00:14:58.350 --> 00:15:01.670
Nixon, you thought I was just making a funny.

00:15:01.670 --> 00:15:10.700
But Nixon famously didn't lead the environmental
movement but he signed into law the EPA, Clean

00:15:10.700 --> 00:15:13.079
Air Act, Clean Water Act right?

00:15:13.079 --> 00:15:18.279
So you can have an arguably crappy President
but if you have a strong enough movement,

00:15:18.279 --> 00:15:21.239
the environmental movement you can actually
get a lot of good things done.

00:15:21.239 --> 00:15:28.180
So really we thought we had all we needed
when we got to Washington DC.

00:15:28.180 --> 00:15:31.420
We had the House with Nancy Pelosi.

00:15:31.420 --> 00:15:34.199
Best speaker ever.

00:15:34.199 --> 00:15:38.879
We had 60 votes in the Senate and we had Barack
Obama as President we thought we had always

00:15:38.879 --> 00:15:39.879
needed.

00:15:39.879 --> 00:15:40.879
It turns out that's one third.

00:15:40.879 --> 00:15:42.670
That's a big take away.

00:15:42.670 --> 00:15:44.360
That's only a third of what you need.

00:15:44.360 --> 00:15:49.209
You also have to have popular movements, the
Tea Party was out there as a popular movement.

00:15:49.209 --> 00:15:52.529
They had a big impact even though they didn't
have governmental control.

00:15:52.529 --> 00:15:56.220
And you have to have big media coordination.

00:15:56.220 --> 00:16:01.699
Fox and the right wing bloggers played a huge
role in impacting policy even though they

00:16:01.699 --> 00:16:04.360
had none of those levers of power.

00:16:04.360 --> 00:16:10.790
I would argue as a Progressive that under
Bush we had the right movement for peace but

00:16:10.790 --> 00:16:11.790
the wrong President.

00:16:11.790 --> 00:16:17.629
And as a Progressive I would say under Obama
we had the right President but the wrong movement,

00:16:17.629 --> 00:16:18.949
the Tea Party.

00:16:18.949 --> 00:16:22.769
So my hope is that going forward we can both
have the right President and the right movement.

00:16:22.769 --> 00:16:25.339
That's what I want to do, that's what the
book is about.

00:16:25.339 --> 00:16:28.850
Can you have the right President who's willing
to be moved by the people.

00:16:28.850 --> 00:16:32.519
But can you also have a movement willing to
do the moving.

00:16:32.519 --> 00:16:34.589
And I think that it's possible.

00:16:34.589 --> 00:16:37.179
And I'll tell you why I think it's possible.

00:16:37.179 --> 00:16:41.350
I think there's a level of economic pain in
the country.

00:16:41.350 --> 00:16:44.339
That it is historic.

00:16:44.339 --> 00:16:48.399
You guys probably have people in your families,
cousins who you went to school with.

00:16:48.399 --> 00:16:53.920
They are not living the lives expected to
live.

00:16:53.920 --> 00:16:58.829
We have people who if you think about a lot
of the young people who are graduating now

00:16:58.829 --> 00:17:04.520
off a cliff into the worst economy since the
Great Depression.

00:17:04.520 --> 00:17:08.949
With massive debt and no jobs.

00:17:08.949 --> 00:17:13.870
That is a relatively new, and I mean people
who went to good schools, who are struggling.

00:17:13.870 --> 00:17:17.270
That is a relatively new development in our
country.

00:17:17.270 --> 00:17:23.910
You think about the young veterans who are
coming home to very little hope.

00:17:23.910 --> 00:17:29.660
Many of them with a lot of psychological and
physical scars.

00:17:29.660 --> 00:17:35.340
When they were overseas they got a chance
to get a lot of support.

00:17:35.340 --> 00:17:37.910
They did some nation building over there.

00:17:37.910 --> 00:17:41.990
You know Halliburton took too big of a cut
of it from my point of view but there they

00:17:41.990 --> 00:17:43.390
are in another country.

00:17:43.390 --> 00:17:50.620
We dump them off at the hometown airport now
with very little support.

00:17:50.620 --> 00:17:54.380
And they go from a military battleground with
a lot of support to an economic battleground

00:17:54.380 --> 00:18:01.250
with very little support and the suicides
are starting to be bigger than the casualties

00:18:01.250 --> 00:18:04.370
of war.

00:18:04.370 --> 00:18:06.670
Now my dad's generation already went through
that.

00:18:06.670 --> 00:18:11.290
I think we should eliminate the term homeless
veteran from the English language.

00:18:11.290 --> 00:18:13.070
That just shouldn't be happening.

00:18:13.070 --> 00:18:14.790
But it is happening.

00:18:14.790 --> 00:18:15.910
You look at the homeowners.

00:18:15.910 --> 00:18:21.570
I mean, we got a quarter of American homes
are underwater right now in terms of financially.

00:18:21.570 --> 00:18:26.530
11 million homes people are spending more
money on the home then the home is worth because

00:18:26.530 --> 00:18:29.640
the home got evaluated during that fantasy
bubble period.

00:18:29.640 --> 00:18:31.100
And so you have people.

00:18:31.100 --> 00:18:35.090
Think about this, this is the American dream
upside down and inside out.

00:18:35.090 --> 00:18:38.510
It used to be if you were a poor person like
my dad.

00:18:38.510 --> 00:18:40.170
How do you get out of poverty?

00:18:40.170 --> 00:18:41.420
And into the middle class.

00:18:41.420 --> 00:18:46.470
You go to college, you buy a home, you're
safe.

00:18:46.470 --> 00:18:51.400
That used to be the pathway out of poverty
into the middle class.

00:18:51.400 --> 00:18:53.500
Not anymore.

00:18:53.500 --> 00:18:57.530
Now that can be the trap door from the middle
class into poverty.

00:18:57.530 --> 00:19:01.210
Because you graduate with all this debt but
you don't have a job.

00:19:01.210 --> 00:19:06.230
And the house you got may not be worth what
the bank told you it was worth.

00:19:06.230 --> 00:19:09.880
And so you got to make a choice do you walk
away?

00:19:09.880 --> 00:19:11.880
Do you keep bleeding yourself dry?

00:19:11.880 --> 00:19:16.960
These are the kind of problems that are new
for the country.

00:19:16.960 --> 00:19:21.450
But when you have problems that big then big
solutions make sense.

00:19:21.450 --> 00:19:28.880
And what I'm hoping to do with this rebuild
the dream idea is to begin to talk about solutions

00:19:28.880 --> 00:19:30.990
at the scale of the problem.

00:19:30.990 --> 00:19:35.530
There's only a couple of ways you get to have
a middle class in your country.

00:19:35.530 --> 00:19:39.140
And it's the middle class right now that's
coming under fire.

00:19:39.140 --> 00:19:43.120
It used to be if you do economic justice work,
you're just trying to get poor people into

00:19:43.120 --> 00:19:44.120
poverty.

00:19:44.120 --> 00:19:47.610
Now you got it try to get poor people out
of poverty and the middle class.

00:19:47.610 --> 00:19:51.670
Now you got it try to keep the middle class
from falling over into poverty, that's a totally

00:19:51.670 --> 00:19:52.990
different fight.

00:19:52.990 --> 00:19:56.770
And it's not a fight for which we are prepared
as a country.

00:19:56.770 --> 00:19:58.290
We haven't thought this all the way through.

00:19:58.290 --> 00:20:03.100
But you can begin to propose solutions at
the scale of the problem if you recognize

00:20:03.100 --> 00:20:06.850
there's only a couple ways you're gonna have
a middle class in your country.

00:20:06.850 --> 00:20:12.880
You're either going to have high skilled manufacturing
jobs or you're going to have a big knowledge

00:20:12.880 --> 00:20:13.880
economy.

00:20:13.880 --> 00:20:14.880
Right?

00:20:14.880 --> 00:20:18.670
Well, we've already given away a lot of our
manufacturing jobs.

00:20:18.670 --> 00:20:23.490
So the only real option for people in a certain
age group, 'cause you can't go get a decent

00:20:23.490 --> 00:20:27.650
job at the factor anymore is to try to go
to college.

00:20:27.650 --> 00:20:29.990
And try to become, get a job here with you
guys.

00:20:29.990 --> 00:20:33.100
That would be a great outcome.

00:20:33.100 --> 00:20:41.410
When I was growing, I was born in '68 for
us it was you know is your kid gonna go to

00:20:41.410 --> 00:20:42.410
law school.

00:20:42.410 --> 00:20:43.680
That was like the big deal.

00:20:43.680 --> 00:20:48.230
You guys, you probably eat lawyers for lunch
you're like, "What, lawyers?"

00:20:48.230 --> 00:20:51.260
[Laughter]
Like it's not, not that big a deal.

00:20:51.260 --> 00:20:54.660
Come and work at Google that's the big deal.

00:20:54.660 --> 00:20:57.680
But how do you get here?

00:20:57.680 --> 00:21:01.960
Somewhere along the way if it didn't happen
at your house, somebody had to have some program,

00:21:01.960 --> 00:21:06.510
some computer summer camping thing, something
had to happen where people got a chance to

00:21:06.510 --> 00:21:10.240
get connected to these jobs of the future.

00:21:10.240 --> 00:21:16.070
The problem is we're the only country in the
world for this next generation that's both

00:21:16.070 --> 00:21:21.060
sending away the manufacturing jobs and making
it harder for people to get educated and go

00:21:21.060 --> 00:21:25.050
to college because of the incredible high
cost of college and the big debt you gotta

00:21:25.050 --> 00:21:26.690
take on.

00:21:26.690 --> 00:21:28.960
That's not just bad for kids.

00:21:28.960 --> 00:21:32.010
It's bad for the country.

00:21:32.010 --> 00:21:37.560
How do you maintain a middle class country
when you have a whole generation you're just

00:21:37.560 --> 00:21:42.560
gonna throw overboard into the global marketplace
with very little help?

00:21:42.560 --> 00:21:46.760
I don't know how America gets to compete in
the world that way.

00:21:46.760 --> 00:21:52.440
So it's not just "Oh you know why should I
care about somebody else's kid.

00:21:52.440 --> 00:21:56.820
When I went to college I paid off my own debt.

00:21:56.820 --> 00:21:58.840
I had several hundred dollars in debt."

00:21:58.840 --> 00:22:01.890
[Laughter]
&gt;&gt;Van Jones: "I paid it off myself."

00:22:01.890 --> 00:22:06.360
I mean you hear this you know.

00:22:06.360 --> 00:22:13.120
And then it's kinda like this failure to understand
that were talking about $25,000 or $50,000

00:22:13.120 --> 00:22:15.240
in debt just for a BS or BA.

00:22:15.240 --> 00:22:20.280
It costs more money now to go to UC Berkeley
than to go to Harvard.

00:22:20.280 --> 00:22:21.280
Why is that?

00:22:21.280 --> 00:22:26.770
It's because we used to think that educating
a generation was good for the country it's

00:22:26.770 --> 00:22:28.160
good for all of us.

00:22:28.160 --> 00:22:32.530
And now we think well maybe it's good for
you, you and your kids good luck.

00:22:32.530 --> 00:22:39.180
It's a fast glide path down to a third rate
status for a country if you do that.

00:22:39.180 --> 00:22:47.120
So we think it's an opportunity to try to
become a nation of neighbors again.

00:22:47.120 --> 00:22:56.860
That American dream which is very easy to
make fun of if you already got it.

00:22:56.860 --> 00:23:02.930
If you're kinda on the cosmopolitan coast
of the country or some of those like blue

00:23:02.930 --> 00:23:05.530
dot college towns it's very easy to pooh-pooh.

00:23:05.530 --> 00:23:10.400
"That's just consumerism.

00:23:10.400 --> 00:23:11.400
Commercialism."

00:23:11.400 --> 00:23:18.120
Maybe.

00:23:18.120 --> 00:23:19.120
That's not all it is.

00:23:19.120 --> 00:23:20.790
That's not the best part of it.

00:23:20.790 --> 00:23:28.530
You know first thing Dr. King said about his
dream, he said "I have a dream.

00:23:28.530 --> 00:23:33.120
It's a dream deeply rooted in the American
dream."

00:23:33.120 --> 00:23:34.530
He wasn't talking about commercialism.

00:23:34.530 --> 00:23:37.050
He wasn't talking about consumerism.

00:23:37.050 --> 00:23:42.510
He was talking about living in a country where
everybody counts.

00:23:42.510 --> 00:23:44.280
Where everybody's dreams matter.

00:23:44.280 --> 00:23:50.980
You shouldn't have to be born rich or of parents
with a famous last name to be able to work

00:23:50.980 --> 00:23:52.260
hard and get somewhere.

00:23:52.260 --> 00:23:56.970
To be able to work hard and get somewhere
and give your kid something better than what

00:23:56.970 --> 00:24:00.270
you got.

00:24:00.270 --> 00:24:04.600
People have come here from all around the
world, all around the world.

00:24:04.600 --> 00:24:07.980
Just to try to get a little piece of that
promise.

00:24:07.980 --> 00:24:11.320
And you know my family we're African-American
we didn't choose to come here but we chose

00:24:11.320 --> 00:24:13.410
to stay because of the beauty of that promise.

00:24:13.410 --> 00:24:18.120
And I don't think we should just let it be
thrown overboard because some folks don't

00:24:18.120 --> 00:24:22.110
want to pay their taxes because we decided
that we can just all go on our individual

00:24:22.110 --> 00:24:23.110
routes.

00:24:23.110 --> 00:24:24.110
We are still one country.

00:24:24.110 --> 00:24:25.480
And were gonna rise or fall together.

00:24:25.480 --> 00:24:28.830
We're gonna turn to each other or on each
other.

00:24:28.830 --> 00:24:31.190
To each other or on each other.

00:24:31.190 --> 00:24:35.460
And our hope is that we can find some common
ground now.

00:24:35.460 --> 00:24:39.630
Because the pain, and will have this nonsense
for, till November.

00:24:39.630 --> 00:24:42.810
It's just the way DC works.

00:24:42.810 --> 00:24:47.180
But my hope is that, my hopes are pinned on
December.

00:24:47.180 --> 00:24:52.341
I think in December we have a chance to stand
together again look in the eyes of these young

00:24:52.341 --> 00:24:53.360
people.

00:24:53.360 --> 00:24:55.260
They're in red states and blue states.

00:24:55.260 --> 00:24:58.180
They're liberals, they're conservatives.

00:24:58.180 --> 00:25:03.380
They're people of faith they're people of
no faith.

00:25:03.380 --> 00:25:08.310
Some of them like a Game of Thrones, some
like Avatar you know you've met these people.

00:25:08.310 --> 00:25:12.230
And they deserve a shot.

00:25:12.230 --> 00:25:16.390
They deserve a shot.

00:25:16.390 --> 00:25:23.710
And I would reject any idea now that says
you're a great patriot if you say "I just

00:25:23.710 --> 00:25:27.840
believe in liberty, individual liberty, good
luck to you."

00:25:27.840 --> 00:25:32.990
That there is no other value in America that's
worth defending than just individual economic

00:25:32.990 --> 00:25:34.210
liberty.

00:25:34.210 --> 00:25:36.440
For you.

00:25:36.440 --> 00:25:44.040
I believe in liberty and justice for all.

00:25:44.040 --> 00:25:48.220
It's a different way of looking at the country.

00:25:48.220 --> 00:25:56.070
Yes liberty, yes economic liberty, yes markets,
yes the opportunity to excel.

00:25:56.070 --> 00:26:00.540
But if all you have is that, you don't have
a country.

00:26:00.540 --> 00:26:04.560
If that's all you've got, you don't have a
country.

00:26:04.560 --> 00:26:09.540
We learned in the last century I'll say in
conclusion that if you just care about justice

00:26:09.540 --> 00:26:14.190
and you don't care about liberty you get totalitarianism.

00:26:14.190 --> 00:26:15.530
That's the big lesson of the last century.

00:26:15.530 --> 00:26:20.860
"In the name of justice, were gonna obliterate
people's economic freedom, their individual

00:26:20.860 --> 00:26:22.790
liberty in the name of justice."

00:26:22.790 --> 00:26:24.380
And what ya got, totalitarianism.

00:26:24.380 --> 00:26:26.530
That was the big lesson of the last century.

00:26:26.530 --> 00:26:30.770
Justice without liberty is totalitarianism.

00:26:30.770 --> 00:26:33.230
In this century we got to learn a different
lesson.

00:26:33.230 --> 00:26:35.010
Keep that one and learn something more.

00:26:35.010 --> 00:26:39.620
If all you've got is individual economic liberty
and no justice.

00:26:39.620 --> 00:26:41.710
No concern about justice for all.

00:26:41.710 --> 00:26:43.320
No concern about the community.

00:26:43.320 --> 00:26:45.180
No concern about the next generation.

00:26:45.180 --> 00:26:48.420
No concern about your neighbor.

00:26:48.420 --> 00:26:53.380
You wind up with a different kind of tyranny.

00:26:53.380 --> 00:26:59.380
You wind up with the kind of not excess concentration
of political power, but an excess concentration

00:26:59.380 --> 00:27:00.640
of economic power.

00:27:00.640 --> 00:27:02.730
And a lot of people left behind.

00:27:02.730 --> 00:27:03.730
Good people.

00:27:03.730 --> 00:27:07.200
Who have dreams and whose hopes matter.

00:27:07.200 --> 00:27:10.640
So the book is an attempt to try to bring
us back together.

00:27:10.640 --> 00:27:14.080
Throw a couple punches at some ideas I don't
like.

00:27:14.080 --> 00:27:18.890
But also hopefully to be able to put that
ladder back up so we can keep the climb going

00:27:18.890 --> 00:27:22.430
toward a country with liberty and justice
for all.

00:27:22.430 --> 00:27:29.480
Thank you so much.

00:27:29.480 --> 00:27:33.010
[Applause]
Questions?

00:27:33.010 --> 00:27:38.680
&gt;&gt;male#1: Hi, it's amazing to see you speak
here.

00:27:38.680 --> 00:27:42.450
I'm wondering if you could tell me why you
think college is so expensive today compared

00:27:42.450 --> 00:27:44.090
to in the past.

00:27:44.090 --> 00:27:47.140
&gt;&gt;Van Jones: Well it's two things.

00:27:47.140 --> 00:27:51.210
The cost of education is not significantly
higher.

00:27:51.210 --> 00:27:56.620
It's the price of education for the individual
young person.

00:27:56.620 --> 00:27:59.430
There's something, something has gotten out
of alignment.

00:27:59.430 --> 00:28:03.910
Part of it is that the private schools are
different conversation but I'm mainly concerned

00:28:03.910 --> 00:28:05.330
about the public schools.

00:28:05.330 --> 00:28:09.350
Schools like UC Berkeley that now cost more
than Harvard.

00:28:09.350 --> 00:28:14.380
It used to be the case that again we thought
that it was good for society to have all these

00:28:14.380 --> 00:28:15.380
kids educated.

00:28:15.380 --> 00:28:16.810
And so therefore college was free.

00:28:16.810 --> 00:28:20.410
Practically free, if you know anybody here
from New York?

00:28:20.410 --> 00:28:26.210
Alright, so the CUNY system was free until,
into my lifetime right?

00:28:26.210 --> 00:28:31.020
And then we decided that it didn't make a
lot ofâ¦

00:28:31.020 --> 00:28:32.900
Since we wanted to have some economic.

00:28:32.900 --> 00:28:35.950
What did you say Nina?

00:28:35.950 --> 00:28:37.160
Okay sorry.

00:28:37.160 --> 00:28:38.990
And produced Nina.

00:28:38.990 --> 00:28:44.110
See, Nina is here from one part of your team
who came from that system.

00:28:44.110 --> 00:28:47.800
So a lot of good people can make that claim.

00:28:47.800 --> 00:28:51.120
But we backed away from the public commitment.

00:28:51.120 --> 00:28:54.700
And there's really only two ways to pay for,
three ways to pay for school.

00:28:54.700 --> 00:28:58.680
Debt, the individual family, and the taxpayer.

00:28:58.680 --> 00:29:03.740
And as the families aren't making a ton of
more money and as the taxpayer backs away

00:29:03.740 --> 00:29:06.200
what happens is that debt gets bigger and
bigger.

00:29:06.200 --> 00:29:09.600
So now we've gotta take a look at this as
a country.

00:29:09.600 --> 00:29:12.900
And I don't think either the Right or the
Left have all the answers on this.

00:29:12.900 --> 00:29:16.560
But I will tell you something that shocking.

00:29:16.560 --> 00:29:18.800
This month, what's the date of it Natalie.

00:29:18.800 --> 00:29:27.280
April 20, April 25 this month there's going
to be, were gonna hit this historic marker

00:29:27.280 --> 00:29:28.610
of shame.

00:29:28.610 --> 00:29:32.980
$1 trillion of student debt in the US economy.

00:29:32.980 --> 00:29:33.990
$1 trillion.

00:29:33.990 --> 00:29:41.990
You say well, it's a rich country maybe $1
trillion dumped on this next generation is

00:29:41.990 --> 00:29:42.990
not that much money.

00:29:42.990 --> 00:29:46.920
Let me give you a sense of how much money
that is.

00:29:46.920 --> 00:29:53.140
That's more than all of the credit card debt
in America combined.

00:29:53.140 --> 00:29:57.480
Take all, wander around taking everybody's
credit card out in the whole country pile

00:29:57.480 --> 00:29:58.660
it up.

00:29:58.660 --> 00:30:03.760
It's a smaller pile of debt then just what
we have right now in student debt.

00:30:03.760 --> 00:30:06.960
So that's bad.

00:30:06.960 --> 00:30:09.630
I don't want to get too technical.

00:30:09.630 --> 00:30:12.580
[Laughter]
That's bad.

00:30:12.580 --> 00:30:16.240
And so we've got to, there's something wrong.

00:30:16.240 --> 00:30:19.450
And I'm sure that there is plenty of blame
to go around.

00:30:19.450 --> 00:30:22.560
But the thing about young people and I see
some people in here who look like you might

00:30:22.560 --> 00:30:23.560
be young.

00:30:23.560 --> 00:30:27.110
The thing about young people is when you have
a system like an education system that goes

00:30:27.110 --> 00:30:28.110
haywire.

00:30:28.110 --> 00:30:31.370
